{"cursor":"6445","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox song|\n| Name = Everyday Cover = Buddy-holly-everyday-coral-1957.jpg Artist = Buddy\n| Holly from Album = Buddy Holly Released = September 20, 1957 http://www.hotshotdigital.com/WellAlwaysRemember/BuddyHollyDisco.html\n| discography Format = Vinyl record Recorded = May 29, 1957 Genre = Rock\n| and roll Length = 2:09 Label = Coral Writer = Buddy\n| Holly, Norman Petty Producer = Norman Petty, Bob Thiele\n}} {{Infobox single \n| Name =Everyday Cover =  Border = Alt = Caption =\n| Artist =John Denver Album =Aerie A-side = B-side =\"City of New Orleans\"\n| Released =1972 Format = Recorded = Genre = Length =  Label\n| =RCA Records Writer = Producer =Milton Okun Certification = Chronology = Last\n| single = \"Friends With You\"  (1971) This single = '\"Everyday\"' \n| (1972) Next single = \"Goodbye Again\"  (1972) Misc =\n}} \"'Everyday'\" is a song written by Buddy Holly and Norman Petty, recorded by\nBuddy Holly and the Crickets on May 29, 1957 and released on September 20, 1957\nas the B-side to \"Peggy Sue\". On the original single the Crickets are not\nmentioned, but it is known that Holly plays acoustic guitar; drummer Jerry\nAllison slaps his hands on his lap for percussion; Joe B. Mauldin plays a\nstandup acoustic bass; [http://buddyholly.pagesperso-orange.fr/page3.htm\nBuddy Holly timeline] and producer Norman Petty's wife, Vi, plays the\nceleste (a keyboard instrument with a glockenspiel-like tone, used in such\nclassical pieces as \"Dance of the Sugarplum Fairy\" from [[The Nutcracker]]). The\nsong length is an economical 2 minutes and 5 seconds. The song is ranked #236 on\nthe [[Rolling Stone]] magazine's list of The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time.\n","linknr":244,"url":"Everyday_(Buddy_Holly_song)","recorded":1374548700,"links":["//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0